entry.title: Beach Hazards Statement issued November 2 at 2:46AM PST until November 4 at 3:00AM PST by NWS San Francisco CA
entry.summary:

* WHERE...Pacific Coast beaches.
* WHEN...From 7 AM PDT this morning through late Monday night.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 2 at 4:30AM CST by NWS Kansas City/Pleasant Hill MO
entry.summary: Satellite imagery is showing fog development along much of the Missouri River early Sunday morning. Department of transportation cameras along bridges of the Missouri River have captured the fog over the past few hours. This includes several bridges in the Kansas City Metro over the river. A few miles on either side of the river, conditions are not as foggy. Please use caution if driving across the Missouri River this morning on any highways or interstates. If the fog should develop further away from the river, a westward expansion of the dense fog advisory currently over central Missouri could become necessary.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Atchison; Doniphan; Leavenworth; Wyandotte; Holt; Buchanan; Platte; Clay; Ray; Jackson; Lafayette

entry.title: Winter Weather Advisory issued November 2 at 1:05AM AKDT until November 2 at 4:00AM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
...ACCUMULATING SNOWFALL NEAR WHITE PASS...
.A front moving through tonight is bringing light to moderate snow to the far northern panhandle. The advisory has been extended in time until early Sunday morning with a slower arrival of the front. The heaviest snow will be at higher elevations near White Pass into early Sunday morning. Snowfall rates will diminish through Sunday.
* WHAT...Snow. Additional snow accumulations of up to three inches. Winds gusting as high as 30 mph.
* WHERE...Higher elevations along the Klondike Highway, especially near White Pass.
* WHEN...Until 4 AM AKDT early this morning.
* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery conditions.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...|Up to moderate snowfall rates are expected to continue into tonight. Snowfall rates will taper down through Sunday.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Municipality of Skagway

entry.title: Hydrologic Outlook issued November 2 at 11:45AM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
ESFGUM
This Hydrologic Outlook is for Guam, Rota, Tinian and Saipan.
A tropical disturbance developing in central Micronesia, is expected to move toward the Marianas in the next few days and bring heavy downpours to the area around midweek. After the storm's passage to the west, feeder bands along the leeside of the system may bring an extended period of rainfall for the rest of the week.
Moderate uncertainty remains regarding potential rainfall impacts, but early estimates indicate this system to bring locally heavy rainfall of 5 to 8 inches across the Marianas by the weekend. This feature will be monitored closely over the next several days by various agencies, so expected rainfall totals may change. Even so, flash flooding remains a possibility Wednesday through Saturday.
As showers are likely to persist, consistent rainfall is likely to saturate the soils enough to increase mudslide risk by the weekend, especially at Guam.
Residents on these islands need to closely monitor this developing situation as flood watches, advisories and flash flood warnings could be issued later.
If living near streams and rivers, prepare to move items away from stream and river banks. Make sure storm drains nearby are not clogged, especially If living at low-lying areas.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Guam, GU; Rota, MP; Saipan, MP; Tinian, MP

entry.title: High Surf Advisory issued November 1 at 1:49PM PDT until November 4 at 3:00AM PST by NWS Los Angeles/Oxnard CA
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Large breaking waves of 10 to 16 feet with dangerous rip currents. Largest surf focused across northwest facing beaches this evening into Sunday morning.
* WHERE...San Luis Obispo County Beaches and Santa Barbara County Central Coast Beaches.
* WHEN...Until 3 AM PDT Tuesday.
* IMPACTS...There is an increased risk for ocean drowning. Rip currents can pull swimmers and surfers out to sea. Large breaking waves can cause injury, wash people off beaches and rocks, and capsize small boats near shore.
